As all documentary records of Kameyama Shrine were lost during the [[Sengoku period]] when [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]]'s forces invaded [[Kii Province]], the foundation of the shrine is uncertain. Its name appears in the ''[[Engishiki]]'' records dated 927 AD, by which time it was a substantial shrine, and the ''[[kofun]]'' located behind the ''[[Honden]]'' had been identified as the tomb of Itsuse no Mikoto by the [[Imperial Household Agency|Imperial household]]. In records dated 1381, the head ''[[kannushi]]'' of the shrine was a hereditary position held by the Ukai family, who claimed to be descendants of the [[Kofun period]] ''[[kuni no miyatsuko]]'' of Kii Province. The shrine was destroyed in 1585 by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, and restored in 1600 by [[:en:Asano Yoshinaga|Asano Yoshinaga]], albeit on a much smaller scale. In 1669 [[Tokugawa Yorinobu]], the first ''[[:en:Daimyō|Daimyō]]'' of [[Kishū Domain]] sponsored the rebuilding of the ''Honden'' and surrounding structures; however, throughout the [[:en:Edo Period|Edo Period]], the shrine was under the control of the domain's ''[[jisha-bugyō]]'' and had no parishioners or outside sources of income.{{cn|date=January 2024}}
Following the [[Meiji Restoration|Meiji restoration]], the shrine was initially accorded the Rank of village shrine under the [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto Shrines|modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]] in 1873. However, with the development of [[State Shinto]] and increasing emphasis on Emperor Jimmu, the shrine was promoted to {{nihongo|Imperial Shrine, 2nd Rank|官幣中社|[[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|Kanpei Chūsha]]}} in 1885 and then to {{nihongo|Imperial Shrine, 1st Rank|官幣大社|Kanpei-taisha}} in 1915. It is the only example of a shrine which was promoted from the lowest Rank to the highest range in the Ranking system. The shrine was extensively remodeled in 1938.
The {{nihongo|Kameyama Tomb|竈山墓||}} is a [[Round Kofun|circular-type]] ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}) ''kofun'', with a height of one meter and diameter of six meters, located on a hill with an elevation of nine meters. As it has been designated as an imperial tomb by the [[Imperial Household Agency]], [[archaeological excavation]] has been prohibited.
