Following the [[Meiji Restoration|Meiji restoration]], the shrine was initially accorded the Rank of village shrine under the [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto Shrines|modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]] in 1873. However, with the development of [[State Shinto]] and increasing emphasis on Emperor Jimmu, the shrine was promoted to {{nihongo|Imperial Shrine, 2nd Rank|官幣中社|[[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|Kanpei Chūsha]]}} in 1885 and then to {{nihongo|Imperial Shrine, 1st Rank|官幣大社|Kanpei-taisha}} in 1915. It is the only example of a shrine which was promoted from the lowest Rank to the highest range in the Ranking system. The shrine was extensively remodeled in 1938.
The {{nihongo|Kameyama Tomb|竈山墓||}} is a [[Round Kofun|circular-type]] ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}) ''kofun'', with a height of one meter and diameter of six meters, located on a hill with an elevation of nine meters. As it has been designated as an imperial tomb by the [[Imperial Household Agency]], [[archaeological excavation]] has been prohibited.
